      <acqinfo id="aspace_8e2753a7914605a71c49954e5d70a9da">
        <head>Acquisition Information</head>
        <p>This collection, comprised exclusively of photocopies, was purchased from Pat Turner
          Ritchie beginning in May 1991 through 2002.</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <custodhist id="aspace_5b988beffaf647452208ecb2e896d577">
        <head>Provenance</head>
        <p>Many of the original documents photocopied in this collection were brought by local
          residents to the Turner Hams Store on Route 259 in Fulks Run, or the nearby Mt. Carmel
          Church, for the "Brocks Gap Heritage Day" events first held by compiler Patricia Turner
          Ritchie in the spring of 1991, where they were copied. Other materials were located by
          Ritchie through her own research. Ritchie created an annotated index for some of the
          materials, and notes that some of the documents are not recorded in the Rockingham County
          Court House.</p>
      </custodhist>
      <processinfo id="aspace_48ecba8c7e3ef9f02794e4fe9866318c">
        <head>Processing Information</head>
        <p>In order to streamline the process of applying collection numbers, Special Collections
          staff completed a large-scale renumbering campaign in the spring of 2017. <emph
            render="bold">This collection was previously cataloged as SC 3088.</emph></p>
      </processinfo>
    </descgrp>
    <bioghist id="aspace_5589ec536ad5e1a6e8aa3a8a6b1e1df4">
      <head>Bio/Historical Note</head>
      <p>Brocks Gap is an area of approximately 200 square miles in northwestern Rockingham County
        formed by the North Fork of the Shenandoah River.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent id="aspace_17f6790a8a2d4538e2f578edbdd3ee8b">
      <head>Scope and Content</head>
      <p>The Patricia Turner Ritchie Collection on Brocks Gap, 1750s-1990s, is comprised exclusively
        of photocopies of deeds, wills, surveys, patents, road agreements, accounts, letters and a
        wide variety of other documents relevant to the Brocks Gap area of northwestern Rockingham
        County, Virginia. The materials document many aspects of rural life. Family names mentioned
        most frequently are Fawley, Fulk, Turner, and Ruddle, but many others also occur. The "C"
        series are papers from the Ransom Hess estate; he was the son of Richard and Lydia Shoemaker
        Hess, grandson of Abraham and Amanda Custer Hess, great grandson of Richard Custer Jr. and
        Elizabeth Trumbo Custer, and lived on the Custer homestead on Little Dry River Road in Fulks
        Run.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement id="aspace_bf6146091507a789c6a22b68ddee104c">
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>The collection is arranged into informal series or groupings of documents: Brocks Gap (BG),
        Fulks Run (F), Custer (C), and Turner (T). This arrangement was imposed by the donor. Each
        document or set of documents was also assigned a numeric identifier by the donor.
        Corresponding indices are included for the Brocks Gap and Fulks Run documents.</p>
    </arrangement>
    <originalsloc id="aspace_f001d2137a2cd44cc0def7a71f398e0c">
      <head>Location of Originals</head>
      <p>Original documents are either retained by private owners or collections in other
        repositories that Ritchie consulted as part of her research.</p>
    </originalsloc>
